    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1872-06-02T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1872-06-02T00:00:00-05:00" n="217" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d217">
                <head>No. 82.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Fish</persName> to General <persName type="to">Schenck</persName>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1872-06-02">
                            <hi rend="italic">June</hi> 2,
                                1872</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Although by a literal construction of the Senate Article, cases of bad
                            faith or willful misconduct may be held to be within its scope, it is
                            inconceivable that such cases can ever be the subject of diplomatic
                            correspondence with a view to pecuniary compensation between two Powers
                            such as those now concerned.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>FISH.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
